<H1>    WKDAY() and wkdayc() </H1>


<H2> Fortran version: </H2>
<PRE>
    INTEGER FUNCTION  WKDAY( JDATE )
        INTEGER, INTENT(IN   ) :: JDATE	!  Julian date (YYYYDDD)
</PRE><P> 

<H2> C version:   </H2>
<PRE>
    int wkdayc( int  jdate ) ;
</PRE><P> 

<H2> Summary: </H2>

    WKDAY() returns the day-of week <STRONG>(1=Monday, ..., 7=Sunday)</STRONG>
    corresponding to the <A HREF = "DATETIME.html"> Julian date JDATE </A> 
    using the Zeller's-congruence algorithm.
<P> 

    See also subroutines 
    <A HREF = "DAYMON.html"> DAYMON()</A>,
    <A HREF = "JULIAN.html"> JULIAN()</A>,
    <A HREF = "MMDDYY.html"> MMDDYY()</A>,
    and <A HREF = "DT2STR.html"> DT2STR() </A> 
    as well as EDSS/ Models-3 date-time manipulation programs
    <A HREF = "GREGDATE.html"> <STRONG>gregdate</STRONG></A> and
    <A HREF = "JULDATE.html">  <STRONG> juldate</STRONG></A>.
    <P> 


<H2> Preconditions:   </H2>

    <CODE>#include &quot;iodecl3.h&quot;</CODE> for C declaration,
    or <CODE><A HREF = "M3UTILIO.html">USE M3UTILIO</A></CODE>
    for Fortran-90 declarations and interface checking.
<P> 

<H2> Fortran Usage: </H2>
<PRE>
    ...
    USE M3UTILIO
    ...
    INTEGER   JDATE, IDAY
    ...
    IDAY = WKDAY( 1988001 )
C	    Now IDAY is day of the week for Jan. 1, 1988
    ...
</PRE><P> 

<H2> C Usage: </H2>
<PRE>
    ...
    #include &quot;iodecl3.h&quot;                          
    ...
    int  wday ;
    ...
    wday = wkdayc( 1988001 ) ;
            /*  Now IDAY is day of the week for Jan. 1, 1988  */
    ...
</PRE><P> 



